# Amazon EBS - Hands-On Lab

## Overview

This lab demonstrates how to create, attach, format, mount, resize, and remove an Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) volume attached to an EC2 instance.

## AWS Services

- Amazon EC2
- Amazon EBS

---

# Architecture

EC2 Instance
        │
        │ Attach
        ▼
 Amazon EBS Volume
        │
        ▼
 Linux File System (ext4)

---

# Objectives

- Create an EBS Volume
- Attach the volume to an EC2 instance
- Format the volume with ext4
- Mount the volume
- Verify persistence
- Resize the volume
- Remove the volume safely

---

# Step 1 - Create an EBS Volume

Created a new General Purpose SSD (gp3) volume in the same Availability Zone as the EC2 instance.

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/create-ebs-volume.png
```

---

# Step 2 - Attach the Volume

Attached the EBS volume to the EC2 instance as:

```
/dev/xvdf
```

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/attach-volume.png
```

---

# Step 3 - Verify the Device

Connected through SSH and verified the new disk.

```bash
lsblk
```

Output confirms the presence of the new block device.

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/lsblk-before-format.png
```

---

# Step 4 - Create a File System

Formatted the new disk using ext4.

```bash
sudo mkfs -t ext4 /dev/xvdf
```

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/mkfs.png
```

---

# Step 5 - Mount the Volume

Created the mount directory.

```bash
sudo mkdir /data
```

Mounted the EBS volume.

```bash
sudo mount /dev/xvdf /data
```

Verified successfully.

```bash
df -h
```

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/mounted-volume.png
```

---

# Step 6 - Automatic Mount After Reboot

Retrieved the UUID.

```bash
sudo blkid
```

Added the volume inside:

```
/etc/fstab
```

Tested configuration.

```bash
sudo mount -a
```

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/fstab.png
```

---

# Step 7 - Resize the Volume

Modified the EBS volume size from the AWS Console.

Expanded the filesystem.

```bash
sudo growpart
```

```bash
sudo resize2fs
```

Verified with:

```bash
df -h
```

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/resize-volume.png
```

---

# Step 8 - Detach and Delete

Unmounted the filesystem.

```bash
sudo umount /data
```

Detached and deleted the EBS volume from AWS.

📷 Screenshot

```
screenshots/delete-volume.png
```

---

# What I Learned

- EBS volumes are network-attached storage.
- An EBS volume must be located in the same Availability Zone as the EC2 instance.
- Volumes can be detached and attached to another instance.
- File systems must be created before mounting.
- UUIDs should be used in `/etc/fstab`.
- Storage can be resized without data loss.

---

